<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-06-21T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-06-21T21:00:00-05:00" n="535" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d535">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1123 Lincheng/167: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-06-22T10:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 22,
                                        1923—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received June 22—5:08
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>234. My 229, June 19, 2 [<hi rend="italic">1</hi>] p.m., and 223, June
                            14, 5 p.m. For exemplary and punitive damages suffered by himself and
                            family in Lincheng outrage, Major Allen has presented claim of $50,000
                            gold and Major Pinger $60,000. I am informed that Shanghai victims of
                            the outrage are presenting still larger claims.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>